<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="354" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[685,1173,268,953]" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,813,268,289]" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The black head, unicolorous elytra, and appendiculate claws distinguish this species from others of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1887" box="[929,1005,321,342]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Triarius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[929,1005,321,342]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">Triarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Wilcox" authorityYear="1965" box="[1110,1172,321,342]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Triarius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pini">
<emphasis box="[1110,1172,321,342]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">T. pini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have dark elytra (
<figureCitation box="[853,923,348,369]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[197,228,1687,1706]" captionTargetBox="[179,1188,443,1668]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[175,1190,441,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 2. Triarius species, dorsal habitus. A) T. pini, male, B) T. pini, female, C) T. trivittatus, D) T. nigroflavus, male, E) T. nigroflavus, female, F) T. melanolomatus, G) T. lividus, H) T. texanus, I) T. novoleonis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3445865" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3445865/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">Fig. 2a</figureCitation>
); females have pale elytra (
<figureCitation box="[692,762,374,395]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[197,228,1687,1706]" captionTargetBox="[179,1188,443,1668]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[175,1190,441,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 2. Triarius species, dorsal habitus. A) T. pini, male, B) T. pini, female, C) T. trivittatus, D) T. nigroflavus, male, E) T. nigroflavus, female, F) T. melanolomatus, G) T. lividus, H) T. texanus, I) T. novoleonis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3445865" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3445865/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">Fig. 2b</figureCitation>
). Specimens measure 5.0–8.0 mm in length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
